Today, on #WorldWildlifeDay, we relive the legacy of our mark, Rajan, the legendary ocean swimming elephant of the Andaman Islands. A symbol of humility, goodness, longevity and strength, Rajan is our reminder for doing the unusual, defying the expected and taking a stand, everyday.

As creators, we have to trust ourselves in what we are making. Trust our taste, our intuition. Rely on many sources of inspiration and past observations. And finally,  go in with a belief that our community will be inspired by what we create. ⁠
⁠
When I (@siddsuri) create, I leave the whole day to just that, to ponder over cads, designs, fabrics, collections. I imagine and anticipate how my consumer will wear each garment. The power of observation is remarkable and the simple act of observing behaviors can lead to superior designs. ⁠
⁠
I align each piece to a collection, each collection to my overall vision for an authentic, loved, homegrown brand. Today @satvikasaboo talked me into documenting some of the processes as we build and strengthen our design direction for the next year.⁠
⁠
--⁠

As the world stood still, witnessing Carlos Alcaraz and Jannik Sinner etch their names into tennis history in what is being debated as one of the greatest match ever played at Roland Garros, another story quietly made its mark beyond the baseline.🌟

Among the sea of spectators was Mr. Yasho Saboo, Founder of Ethos Watch Boutiques — a man of quiet elegance and timeless taste. But what he wore spoke volumes.

Wearing an Andamen polo — the first ever worn by an Indian at the French Open — Mr. Saboo carried the story of a new India. A narrative of proudly wearing India, at a prestigious International event. 🌟

In a setting defined by tradition and prestige, Indian design stood shoulder to shoulder with global icons at the @rolex box. 

This wasn’t just a polo.
It was a flag in motion.
A legacy worn.
A quiet revolution, front row at a Grand Slam.🎾
